io.hekate.metrics.cluster

Interface ClusterMetricsService

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Service

    @DefaultServiceFactory(value=ClusterMetricsServiceFactory.class)
public interface ClusterMetricsService
extends Service
    « start hereMain entry point to cluster-wide metrics API.

    Overview

    The ClusterMetricsService provides support for making the LocalMetricsService's metrics visible to other nodes of the cluster. It periodically replicates snapshots of metrics data between cluster nodes so that applications can implement their own monitoring and load balancing schemes based on their view of the overall cluster performance.

    Note: Metrics replication is performed only among those nodes that have metrics replication enabled.

    For more details about metrics and their usage please see the documentation of LocalMetricsService.

    Service configuration

    Cluster metrics service can be configured and registered in HekateBootstrap with the help of ClusterMetricsServiceFactory as shown in the example below:

    • Java
    • Spring XSD
    • Spring bean
    
// Prepare service factory.
ClusterMetricsServiceFactory factory = new ClusterMetricsServiceFactory()
    // Replicate metrics once per second.
    .withReplicationInterval(1000)
    .withEnabled(true);

// Start node.
Hekate hekate = new HekateBootstrap()
    .withService(factory)
    .join();
    Note: This example requires Spring Framework integration (see HekateSpringBootstrap). 
    
<beans xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xmlns:h="http://www.hekate.io/spring/hekate-core"
    xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
        http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd
        http://www.hekate.io/spring/hekate-core
        http://www.hekate.io/spring/hekate-core.xsd">

    <h:node id="hekate">
        <!-- Cluster metrics service. -->
        <h:cluster-metrics enabled="true" replication-interval-ms="1000"/>

        <!-- ...other services... -->
    </h:node>
</beans>
    Note: This example requires Spring Framework integration (see HekateSpringBootstrap). 
    
<beans xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
        http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd">

    <bean id="hekate" class="io.hekate.spring.bean.HekateSpringBootstrap">
        <property name="services">
            <list>
                <!-- Cluster metrics service. -->
                <bean class="io.hekate.metrics.cluster.ClusterMetricsServiceFactory">
                    <property name="enabled" value="true"/>
                    <property name="replicationInterval" value="1000"/>
                </bean>

                <!-- ...other services... -->
            </list>
        </property>
    </bean>
</beans>

    Note that cluster metrics are disabled by default and should be enabled via the ClusterMetricsServiceFactory.setEnabled(boolean) configuration option. For other configuration options please see the documentation of ClusterMetricsServiceFactory class.

    Accessing service

    Cluster metrics service can be accessed via Hekate.clusterMetrics() method as in the example below: 

    
ClusterMetricsService metrics = hekate.clusterMetrics();

    Usage example

    The code example below shows how ClusterMetricsService can be used to access metrics of cluster nodes: 

    
// Iterate over all remote nodes in the cluster.
hekate.cluster().forRemotes().forEach(node -> {
    // Use cluster metrics service to get metrics of each node.
    hekate.clusterMetrics().of(node).ifPresent(m ->
        System.out.println("Metric on node " + m.node() + " = " + m.get("example.metric"))
    );
});

    Replication protocol details

    ClusterMetricsService uses a periodic synchronization protocol for metrics replication between the cluster nodes.

    All nodes are organized into a ring with each node periodically sending its own metrics as well as all metrics that it received from its predecessor to the next node. The time interval of metrics replication is controlled by the ClusterMetricsServiceFactory.setReplicationInterval(long) configuration option.

    Note that due to the periodic nature of metrics replication algorithm it is possible that some nodes will lag and will see older metrics data than other nodes. How large this lag is depends on the cluster size and the replication interval configuration option.

    See Also:
    ClusterMetricsServiceFactory, LocalMetricsService
